com.launchdarkly.client

Class FeatureStoreCacheConfig

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.launchdarkly.client.FeatureStoreCacheConfig
  • Deprecated. 
    This has been superseded by the PersistentDataStoreBuilder interface.

    @Deprecated
public final class FeatureStoreCacheConfig
extends java.lang.Object
    Parameters that can be used for FeatureStore implementations that support local caching. If a store implementation uses this class, then it is using the standard caching mechanism that is built into the SDK, and is guaranteed to support all the properties defined in this class.

    This is an immutable class that uses a fluent interface. Obtain an instance by calling the static methods disabled() or enabled(); then, if desired, you can use chained methods to set other properties: 

    
     Components.redisFeatureStore()
         .caching(
             FeatureStoreCacheConfig.enabled()
                 .ttlSeconds(30)
                 .staleValuesPolicy(FeatureStoreCacheConfig.StaleValuesPolicy.REFRESH)
         )
    Since:
    4.6.0
    See Also:
    RedisFeatureStoreBuilder.caching(FeatureStoreCacheConfig)

      • getCacheTime

        public long getCacheTime()
        Deprecated. 
        Returns the cache TTL.

        If the value is zero, caching is disabled.

        If the value is negative, data is cached forever (i.e. it will only be read again from the database if the SDK is restarted). Use the "cached forever" mode with caution: it means that in a scenario where multiple processes are sharing the database, and the current process loses connectivity to LaunchDarkly while other processes are still receiving updates and writing them to the database, the current process will have stale data.

        Returns:
        the cache TTL in whatever units were specified
        See Also:
        getCacheTimeUnit()

      • ttl

        public FeatureStoreCacheConfig ttl(long cacheTime,
                                   java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit timeUnit)
        Deprecated. 
        Specifies the cache TTL. Items will be evicted or refreshed (depending on staleValuesPolicy(StaleValuesPolicy)) after this amount of time from the time when they were originally cached. If the time is less than or equal to zero, caching is disabled. after this amount of time from the time when they were originally cached.

        If the value is zero, caching is disabled.

        If the value is negative, data is cached forever (i.e. it will only be read again from the database if the SDK is restarted). Use the "cached forever" mode with caution: it means that in a scenario where multiple processes are sharing the database, and the current process loses connectivity to LaunchDarkly while other processes are still receiving updates and writing them to the database, the current process will have stale data.

        Parameters:
        cacheTime - the cache TTL in whatever units you wish
        timeUnit - the time unit
        Returns:
        an updated parameters object
